# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: british-sign-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:british-sign-language/aaron-cicourel] In November 2007, he was awarded Docteur Honoris Causa by Université de Fribourg in Switzerland, and in 2008 was awarded Doctor Honoris Causa Complutense University of Madrid.
[src:british-sign-language/aaron-cicourel] Cicourel was elected Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the American Association for the Advancement of Science.
[src:british-sign-language/aaron-cicourel] Cicourel was likely the first scholar to use the full name of "British Sign Language" in an academic publication.
[src:british-sign-language/aaron-cicourel] Aaron Cicourel died on July 22, 2023, at the age of 94.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] For over a decade, the deaf children of the village have attended a boarding school in Mampong-Akuapem, where the ASL based Ghanaian Sign Language is used.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] As a consequence, this language has become the first language of these children and their command of AdaSL is decreasing.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] This is likely to lead to a complete shift of the deaf community in Adamorobe to Ghanaian Sign Language.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] As such, AdaSL is an endangered sign language.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Adamorobe is situated approximately 30 to 40 kilometers north of Accra in the Akuapem Hills.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] It is a predominantly Akan village, with the majority of the population speaking the Akan language (Akuapem Twi) in addition to using AdaSL.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The community gained attention for its unusually high incidence of hereditary deafness, a phenomenon that has shaped the village's cultural and linguistic landscape.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many other deaf communities where deaf individuals are socially marginalized, Adamorobe's deaf residents are fully integrated into village life.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Hearing villagers commonly use AdaSL in daily interactions, creating a bilingual environment that bridges the hearing and deaf worlds seamlessly.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL shares signs and prosodic features with some other sign languages in the region, such as Bura Sign Language, but it has been suggested these similarities are due to culturally shared gestures rather than a genetic relationship.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL has features that set it apart from the sign languages of large deaf communities studied so far, including the absence of the type of classifier construction that expresses motion or location (sometimes called "entity classifiers").
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Instead, AdaSL uses several types of serial verb constructions also found in the surrounding spoken language, Akan.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Nancy Frishberg suggests that AdaSL may be related to the "gestural trade jargon used in the markets throughout West Africa".
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Adamorobe Sign Language possesses distinct grammatical structures and vocabulary that set it apart from Ghanaian Sign Language and other national or international sign languages.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many urban sign languages that develop within educational institutions, AdaSL evolved organically within a close-knit community, resulting in unique syntactic constructions and simultaneous sign formations.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Its use is characterized by spatial grammar, classifier constructions, and gestures deeply embedded in the local culture.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The language is not mutually intelligible with GSL, and many signs are specific to Adamorobe's cultural context, making it a rich subject of linguistic study.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL also exhibits a lower reliance on fingerspelling compared to GSL, and it preserves several features that are considered archaic or absent in more standardized sign languages.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Deaf culture in Adamorobe is notably inclusive.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Deaf residents have historically participated fully in social, economic, and cultural activities.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many other societies, deafness in Adamorobe does not carry a stigma.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Instead, sign language has been a natural and respected form of communication, used not only by deaf individuals but also by hearing family members, friends, and neighbors.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] This integration is evident in communal gatherings, marketplaces, and traditional ceremonies where sign language is used openly.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The social fabric of Adamorobe has long celebrated this coexistence, which has contributed to the resilience of its deaf community despite external pressures.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL is believed to have emerged over 200 years ago, alongside the settlement's founding.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Genetic studies suggest that the high incidence of deafness in Adamorobe is due to a hereditary mutation passed down through generations.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The earliest academic references to Adamorobe and its sign language date back to the mid-20th century, with researchers noting the community's unique integration of deaf individuals.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] In the 1960s and 1980s, the introduction of formal deaf education in Ghana led to the exposure of Adamorobe's deaf children to Ghanaian Sign Language, which is derived from American Sign Language (ASL).
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] This exposure began to shift the linguistic practices of younger generations, who now tend to use GSL more frequently than AdaSL.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] A critical turning point in the village's history came in 1975 when the local chief instituted a ban on marriages between deaf individuals in an effort to reduce the incidence of hereditary deafness.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] While this policy effectively decreased the number of deaf births, it also inadvertently threatened the long-term survival of AdaSL.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Today, Adamorobe Sign Language faces significant challenges.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The number of deaf individuals in the village has declined due to the marriage policy that discouraged unions between deaf people.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Additionally, the younger generation of deaf children is increasingly adopting Ghanaian Sign Language through formal education, which reduces the intergenerational transmission of AdaSL.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The influence of urbanization and national language policies further accelerates the shift away from village sign languages.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Without deliberate preservation efforts, AdaSL risks becoming endangered or possibly extinct within the next few decades.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Several linguists and anthropologists have documented Adamorobe Sign Language extensively in recent years.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Their efforts aim to preserve the language's unique features and raise awareness of its cultural importance.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] However, there are limited formal initiatives within the village to revitalize or maintain AdaSL among younger generations.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Potential preservation strategies include community-based language programs, the development of AdaSL teaching materials, and the integration of the language into local schools.
[src:british-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Encouraging the use of AdaSL in social and cultural events could also contribute to its sustainability.
[src:british-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Education for the deaf in Afghanistan grew out of educational efforts among Afghan refugees in Peshawar in the 1990s, making Pakistani Sign Language (IPSL) an early influence on Afghan Sign Language.
[src:british-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] The first formal school for the deaf in Afghanistan was established in Jalalabad in 1995 by SERVE Afghanistan.
[src:british-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] That same year, SERVE began a project to document Afghan Sign Language, and later produced a trilingual (Dari, Pashto, and English) dictionary of Afghan Sign Language.
[src:british-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] The language derives from the Deaf-community sign language of Jalalabad, and it is not known what connection it may have, if any, with the sign languages of other cities with established deaf populations, which are principally Mazar-i-Sharif, Herat, and Kandahar.
[src:british-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Early analysis suggested some AFSL signs may have come from Pakistani Sign Language (IPSL) or American Sign Language (ASL), although intensive research on this link was not undertaken at the time.
[src:british-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] While IPSL's influence would have been due to regional exchange, ASL could have had an influence due to its use by some SERVE teachers in its early programming.
[src:british-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Fingerspelling was introduced to AFSL in the late 1990s, after SERVE educators visited the Holy Land Institute for the Deaf in Jordan.
[src:british-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Thus, Jordanian Sign Language and AFSL share a fingerspelling alphabet, although AFSL also introduced some additional letters to represent letters not found in the Arabic script.
[src:british-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Afghan Sign Language is primarily spoken in Jalalabad and Kabul, which have three large schools for the deaf between them.
[src:british-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Smaller deaf populations who use AFSL are also found in major urban centers in the country, those being Mazar-e Sharif, Herat, and Kandahar.
[src:british-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] The majority of profoundly deaf Afghans (estimated at 30,000 in 2013) have never attended a school for the deaf.
[src:british-sign-language/akitiri-sign-language] Akitiri is often used when speech is impractical or not preferred and this includes when people are communicating across long distances, hunting, when wishing to speak privately and during ceremony and times of mourning.
[src:british-sign-language/akitiri-sign-language] Hand signs are also frequently used alongside speech and is more commonly used by women of the community.
[src:british-sign-language/akitiri-sign-language] In many Kaytetye communities fluency in Akitiri is highly valued but, due to the impacts of colonisation, use is declining and younger generations often use it in a different or simplified way.
[src:british-sign-language/akitiri-sign-language] A 2023 project to revitalise the Kaytetye language and Akitiri sign language was the Kaytetyemoji app which created 122 emojis including 44 specific to life on Kaytetye country.
[src:british-sign-language/akitiri-sign-language] These emoji's often directly reflect the hand signs of Akitiri and, as part of the development of the app, many younger generations were taught new signs to them.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] American Sign Language (ASL) has grammar just like any other sign language or spoken language.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The study of ASL structure dates back to William Stokoe, Dorothy Casterline, and Carl Croneberg in the 1960s.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Since then, linguists have been describing patterns in ASL responsible for creating meaning at all kinds of levels, from the word, to phrases and sentences and beyond.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Not all of these linguists ascribe to the same theoretical framework, using various theories, models, and analyses.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some analyze the language from a generative linguistics perspective, while others from a cognitive linguistics perspective.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL morphology, publications have historically categorized morphological processes under two umbrellas: derivational morphology and inflectional morphology.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Derivational morphology is the process by which new units can be created in a language, and like any other language, this process has been observed in a variety of forms in ASL.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One form of derivational morphology occurs when a change in movement changes the sign's meaning – often between a noun and a verb.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This may be done either by reduplicating the movement of the verb if the verb has a single movement, or by restraining (making smaller and faster) the movement of the verb if it already has repeated movement.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the noun CHAIR is derived from the verb SIT through reduplication.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Another way of deriving new words in ASL is via the process of compounding, which often differ in meaning from their constituent signs.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the signs FACE and STRONG compound to create a new sign FACE^STRONG, meaning 'to resemble'.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some linguists have analyzed various compounds as a type of suffixation.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Agent nouns may be derived from verbs by adding the sign, or suffix, AGENT and deleting the final hold of the verb, e.g.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Superlatives have also been analyzed as created by a formed by suffixation, e.g.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, Ted Supalla's work on ASL verbs of motion analyzed these signs as consisting of many different affixes, articulated simultaneously according to complex grammatical constraints.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This differs from the concatenative morphology of many spoken languages, which except for suprasegmental features, such as tone, are tightly constrained by the sequential nature of voice sounds.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Numeral incorporation is another derivational morphological process that has been studied in ASL.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Certain types of signs, for example, those relating to time and age, may incorporate numbers by assimilating their handshape.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the word for 'week' has handshape /B/ with the weak hand and /1/ with the active hand; the active hand's handshape may be changed to the handshape of any number up to 9 to indicate that many weeks.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some linguists have analyzed this phenomenon as a type of affixation.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Signs of age, for example, will begin with a touch at the chin.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They argue that this touch functions as a prefix which completely assimilates with the handshape of the corresponding age number.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For instance, the word for 'nine' is signed with an /F/ handshape produced ipsilaterally in front of the signer's shoulder.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The chin-touch in 'nine years old' can be analyzed as an affix, which is then produced with this same /F/ handshape.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For 'three years old', however, the prefix is made with a 3 handshape.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Inflectional morphology adds units of language to other words.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, this would be changing 'watch' to 'watches' or 'watching.' In ASL, the sign may remain unchanged as WATCH, or the meaning may change based on non-manual markers (NMM).
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL morphology demonstrates reduplication and indexicality as well.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are about 20 non-manual modifiers in ASL, which are either adjectival or adverbial.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Rather than relying on sequential affixes, ASL makes heavy use of simultaneous modification of signs.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One example of this is found in the aspectual system (see below); another is *numeral incorporation:* There are several families of two-handed signs which require one of the hands to take the handshape of a numeral.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, drawing the dominant hand lengthwise across the palm and fingers of a flat B hand indicates a number of weeks; the dominant hand takes the form of a numeral from one to nine to specify how many weeks.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are analogous signs for 'weeks ago' and 'weeks from now', etc., though in practice several of these signs are only found with the lower numerals.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL also has a system of classifiers which may be incorporated into signs.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These classifiers are moved through sign space to iconically represent the actions of their referents.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, an ILY hand may 'lift off' or 'land on' a horizontal B hand to sign an aircraft taking off or landing; a 3 hand may be brought down on a B hand to sign parking a car; and a G hand may be brought toward a V hand to represent one person approaching two.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The frequency of classifier use depends greatly on genre, occurring at a rate of 17.7% in narratives but only 1.1% in casual speech and 0.9% in formal speech.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Frames are a morphological device that may be unique to sign languages (Liddell 2004).
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They are incomplete sets of the features which make up signs, and they combine with existing signs, absorbing features from them to form a derived sign.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It is the frame which specifies the number and nature of segments in the resulting sign, while the basic signs it combines with lose all but one or two of their original features.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One, the WEEKLY frame, consists of a simple downward movement.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It combines with the signs for the days of the week, which then lose their inherent movement.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, 'Monday' consists of an M/O hand made with a circling movement.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] 'MondayWEEKLY' (that is, 'on Mondays') is therefore signed as an M/O hand that drops downward, but without the circling movement.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A similar ALL DAY frame (a sideward pan) combines with times of the day, such as 'morning' and 'afternoon', which likewise keep their handshape and location but lose their original movement.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Numeral incorporation (see above) also uses frames.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, in ASL frames are most productively utilized for verbal aspect.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] While there is no grammatical tense in ASL, there are numerous verbal aspects.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These are produced by modulating the verb: through reduplication, by placing the verb in an aspectual frame (see above), or with a combination of these means.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] An example of an aspectual frame is the *unrealized inceptive* aspect ('just about to X'), illustrated here with the verb 'to tell'.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] 'To tell' is an indexical (directional) verb, where the index finger (a G hand) begins with a touch to the chin and then moves outward to point out the recipient of the telling.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The handshape throughout the sign is whichever is required by the final hold, in this case a G hand.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The variety of aspects in ASL can be illustrated by the verb 'to be sick', which involves the middle finger of the Y/8 hand touching the forehead, and which can be modified by a large number of frames.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Several of these involve reduplication, which may but need not be analyzed as part of the frame.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These modulations readily combine with each other to create yet finer distinctions.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Not all verbs take all aspects, and the forms they do take will not necessarily be completely analogous to the verb illustrated here.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Conversely, not all aspects are possible with this one verb.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Aspect is unusual in ASL in that transitive verbs derived for aspect lose their transitivity.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Reduplication is also used for expressing verbal number.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Verbal number indicates that the action of the verb is repeated; in the case of ASL it is apparently limited to transitive verbs, where the motion of the verb is either extended or repeated to cover multiple object or recipient loci.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] (Simple plurality of action can also be conveyed with reduplication, but without indexing any object loci; in fact, such aspectual forms do not allow objects, as noted above.) There are specific dual forms (and for some signers trial forms), as well as plurals.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the singular verb uses reduplication, that is lost in the dual and plural forms.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are three types of personal name signs in ASL: fingerspelled, arbitrary, and descriptive.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Fingerspelled names are simply spelled out letter-by-letter.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Arbitrary name signs only refer to a person's name, while descriptive name signs refer to a person's personality or physical characteristics.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Once given, names are for life, apart from changing from one of the latter types to an arbitrary sign in childhood.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Name signs are usually assigned by another member of the Deaf community, and signal inclusion in that community.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Name signs are not used to address people, as names are in English, but are used only for third-person reference, and usually only when the person is absent.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The majority of people, probably well in excess of 90%, have arbitrary name signs.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These are initialized signs: The handshape is the initial of one of the English names of the person, usually the first.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The sign may occur in neutral space, with a tremble; with a double-tap (as a noun) at one of a limited number of specific locations, such as the side of the chin, the temple, or the elbow; or moving across a location or between two locations, with a single tap at each.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Single-location signs are simpler in connotation, like English "Vee"; double-location signs are fancier, like English "Veronica".
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Sam Supalla (1992) collected 525 simple arbitrary name signs like these.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are two constraints on arbitrary signs.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] That is, it should not duplicate an existing ASL word.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Second, there should not be more than one person with the name sign in the local community.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If a person moves to a new community where someone already has their name sign, then the newcomer is obligated to modify theirs.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is usually accomplished by compounding the handshape, so that the first tap of the sign takes the initial of the person's first English name, and the second tap takes the initial of their last name.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are potentially thousands of such compound-initial signs.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Descriptive name signs are not initialized, but rather use non-core ASL signs.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They tend to be assigned and used by children, rather like "Blinky" in English.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Parents do not give such names to their children, but most Deaf people do not have deaf parents and are assigned their name sign by classmates in their first school for the deaf.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] At most 10% of Deaf people retain such name signs into adulthood..
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Arbitrary name signs became established very early in the history of ASL.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Descriptive name signs refer to a person's appearance or personality.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The two systems, arbitrary and descriptive, are sometimes combined, usually for humorous purposes.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Hearing people learning ASL are also often assigned combined name signs.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is not traditional for Deaf people.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Sometimes people with very short English names, such as "Ann" or "Lee", or ones that flow easily, such as "Larry", may never acquire a name sign, but may instead be referred to with finger-spelling.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-Manual Markers (NMM), or Non-Manual Signals (NMS) are communication methods not found in the hands.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They typically consist of facial expressions and body language.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] NMMs can change the grammar of a sentence.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Not every sign uses non-manual markers, but for many others, these markers determine what sign is being produced.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some examples of non-manual markers would be the shifting of shoulders, the lowering or raising of eyebrows, a head nod or shake, scrunching of the nose, pursing of the lips, or an open mouth.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] NMMs are important for indicating if a question is being asked.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For *WH-* questions, the eyebrows are lowered, and for *YES/NO* questions, the eyebrows are raised.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It is hard to indicate if a question is being asked otherwise without facial indicators.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Another example would be between *I UNDERSTAND* and *I DON'T UNDERSTAND*.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The sign for this is the same; the hand is held up near the forehead with the palm facing the self.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the person is nodding and has their eyebrows raised, it means *I UNDERSTAND*.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If they are shaking their head with eyebrows lowered, it means *I DON'T UNDERSTAND*.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Understanding ASL grammar requires understanding the difference between a signer's dominant and non-dominant hand.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If a person is right-handed, then their right hand is their dominant hand, and their left hand is their non-dominant hand.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Almost all signs are completed with the more active, dominant hand, while the non-dominant hand serves as a base.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For signs requiring two hands, the dominant hand performs more of the active component.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL is a subject–verb–object (SVO) language.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, OSV is also an accepted sentence form.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The default SVO word order is sometimes altered by processes including topicalization and null elements.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is marked either with non-manual signals like eyebrow or body position, or with prosodic marking such as pausing.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These non-manual grammatical markings (such as eyebrow movement or head-shaking) may optionally spread over the c-command domain of the node which it is attached to.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, ASL is a pro-drop language, and when the manual sign that a non-manual grammatical marking is attached to is omitted, the non-manual marking obligatorily spreads over the c-command domain.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The full sentence structure in ASL is [topic] [subject] verb [object] [subject–pronoun–tag].
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topics and *tags* are both indicated with non-manual features, and both give a great deal of flexibility to ASL word order.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Within a noun phrase, the word order is noun–number and noun–adjective.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL does not have a copula (linking 'to be' verb).
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In addition to its basic topic–comment structure, ASL typically places an adjective after a noun, though it may occur before the noun for stylistic purposes.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Numerals also occur after the noun, a very rare pattern among oral languages.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Adverbs, however, occur before the verbs.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Most of the time adverbs are simply the same sign as an adjective, distinguished by the context of the sentence.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] When the scope of the adverb is the entire clause, as in the case of time, it comes before the topic.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL makes heavy use of time-sequenced ordering, meaning that events are signed in the order in which they occur.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, for *I was late to class last night because my boss handed me a huge stack of work after lunch yesterday,* one would sign 'YESTERDAY LUNCH FINISH, BOSS GIVE-me WORK BIG-STACK, NIGHT CLASS LATE-me'.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In stories, however, ordering is malleable, since one can choose to sequence the events either in the order in which they occurred or in the order in which one found out about them.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It has been claimed that tense in ASL is marked adverbially, and that ASL lacks a separate category of tense markers.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] (1992, 1995) argue that "Tense" (T) is indeed a distinct category of syntactic head, and that the T node can be occupied either by a modal (e.g.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Aspect may be marked either by verbal inflection or by separate lexical items.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] As noted above, in ASL aspectually marked verbs cannot take objects.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] To deal with this, the object must be known from context so that it does not need to be further specified.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It may be used as the topic of the utterance at hand.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Of these two strategies, the first is the more common.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A topic sets off background information that will be discussed in the following main clause.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topicalization is used productively in ASL and often results in surface forms that do not follow the basic SVO word order.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In order to non-manually mark topics, the eyebrows are raised and the head is tilted back during the production of a topic.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The head is often lowered toward the end of the sign, and sometimes the sign is followed rapidly nodding the head.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Another way topics may be signed is by shifting the body.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The signer may use the space on one side of his/her body to sign the topic, and then shifts to the other side for the rest of the sentence.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL utterances do not require topics, but their use is extremely common.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They are used for purposes of information flow, to set up referent loci (see above), and to supply objects for verbs which are grammatically prevented from taking objects themselves (see below).
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, people tend to want to set up the object of their concern first and then discuss what happened to it.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are three types of non-manual topic markers, all of which involve raised eyebrows.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The three types of non-manual topic markers are used with different types of topics and in different contexts, and the topic markings cannot spread over other elements in the utterance.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topics can be moved from and remain null in the main clause of an utterance, or topics can be base-generated and either be co-referential to either the subject or object in the main clause or be related to the subject of object by a semantic property.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The first type of non-manual marking, topic marking 1 (tm1), is only used with a moved topic.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm1 is characterized by raised eyebrows, widened eyes, and head tilted backwards.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] At the end of the sign the head moves down and there is a pause, often with an eye blink, before the sentence is continued.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topic marking 2 (tm2) and topic marking 3 (tm3) are both used with base-generated topics.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm2 is characterized by raised eyebrows, widened eyes, and the head tilted backwards and to the side.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Toward the end of the sign the head moves forward and to the opposite side, and there is a pause and often an eye blink before continuing.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For tm3 the eyebrows are raised and the eyes are opened wide, the head starts tilted down and jerks up and down, the lips are opened and raised, and the head is nodded rapidly a few times before pausing and continuing the sentence.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Although both tm2 and tm3 accompany base-generated topics, they are used in different contexts.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm2 is used to introduce new information and change the topic of a conversation to something that the signer is going to subsequently characterize, while tm3 is used to introduce new information that the signer believes is already known by his/her interlocutor.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm2 may be used with any base-generated topic, whereas only topics that are co-referential with an argument in the sentence may be marked with tm3.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL sentences may have up to two marked topics.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Possible combinations of topic types are two tm2 topics, two tm3 topics, tm2 preceding tm1, tm3 preceding tm1, and tm2 preceding tm3.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Sentences with these topic combinations in the opposite orders or with two tm1 topics are considered ungrammatical by native signers.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Relative clauses are signaled by tilting back the head and raising the eyebrows and upper lip.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is done during the performance of the entire clause.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] where the brackets here indicate the duration of the non-manual features.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the sign 'recently' were made without these features, it would lie outside the relative clause, and the meaning would change to "the dog which chased the cat recently came home".
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Negated clauses may be signaled by shaking the head during the entire clause.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A topic, however, cannot be so negated; the headshake can only be produced during the production of the main clause.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In addition, in many communities, negation is put at the end of the clause, unless there is a wh- question word.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the sentence, "I thought the movie was not good," could be signed as, "BEFORE MOVIE ME SEE, THINK WHAT?
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are two manual signs that negate a sentence, NOT and NONE, which are accompanied by a shake of the head.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are three types of questions with different constructions in ASL: wh- questions, yes/no questions, and rhetorical questions.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings are grammatical and semantic features that do not include the use of hands.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They can include mouth shape, eye gazes, facial expressions, body shifting, head tilting, and eyebrow raising.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings can also aid in identifying sentence type, which is especially relevant to our discussion of different types of interrogatives.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Wh-questions can be formed in a variety of ways in ASL.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The wh-word can appear solely at the end of the sentence, solely at the beginning of the sentence, at both the beginning and end of the sentence (see section 4.4.2.1 on 'double-occurring wh-words', or in situ (i.e. where the wh-word is in the sentence structure before movement occurs)).
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Manual wh-signs are also accompanied by a non-manual grammatical marking (see section 4.4.1), which can include a variety of features.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This non-manual grammatical marking can spread optionally over the entire wh-phrase or just a small part.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some languages have very few wh-words, where context and discourse are sufficient to elicit the information that one needs.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL has many different wh-words, with certain wh-words having multiple variations.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A list of the wh-words of ASL can be found below.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] As mentioned above, ASL possesses wh-questions with word initial placement, word final placement, in situ structure, but the most unique style of wh-word occurrence in ASL is where the wh-word occurs twice, copied in final position.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This doubling can be seen in the table below.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This doubling provides a useful template to analyze two separate analyses about whether wh-words move rightward or leftward in ASL.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] While some researchers argue for rightward movement in wh- questions such as Aarons and Neidle, others, including Petronio and Lillo-Martin, have argued that ASL has leftward movement and wh- words that appear to the right of the clause move by other processes.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Both analyses agree upon the fact that there is wh-movement present in these interrogative phrases, but it is a matter of what direction the wh-movement is moving in that causes controversy.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The leftward movement analysis is congruent with cross-linguistic data that wh-movement is always leftward.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It can be seen as the less controversial of the two proposals.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The main arguments presented by the Leftward Wh-movement analysis are: That the spec-CP is on the left, that the wh-movement is leftward, and that the final wh-word in a sentence is a base-generated double.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is illustrated in the syntax tree located to the right of this paragraph.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Arguments for leftward movement are based on the facts that if wh-movement in ASL were rightward, ASL would be an exception to cross-linguistic generalizations that wh-movement is leftward.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It has also been hypothesized that wh-elements cannot be topicalized, as topicalized elements must be presupposed and interrogatives are not.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This would be detrimental to the rightward analysis, as they are analyzing the doubled wh-word as a 'base generated topic'.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The rightward movement analysis is a newer, more abstract argument of how wh-movement occurs in ASL.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The main arguments for rightward movement begin by analyzing spec-CP as being on the right, the wh-movement as being rightward, and as the initial wh-word as a base-generated topic.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This can be seen in the syntax tree on the right.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One of the rightward movement analysis' main arguments is in regards to the non-manual grammatical markings, and their optional spreading over the sentence.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL the use of non-manual grammatical markings is optional depending on the type of wh-question being asked.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In the rightward analysis both partial and full spreading of non-manual grammatical markers can be accounted for due to the association with the +WH feature over its c-command domain.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In the leftward analysis, the partial or full spreading of non manual grammatical markings cannot be accounted for in this same way.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The leftward movement analysis requires wh-marking to extend over the entirety of the question, regardless (which is not what is attested in ASL).
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In spoken language Yes/no questions will oftentimes differ in their word order from the statement form.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL, yes/no questions are marked by the non-manual grammatical markings (as discussed in section 4.4.1).
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This eyebrow raise, slight tilt of the head and lean forward are what indicate that a yes/no question is being asked, without any change in word order from the statement form.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There is speculation amongst linguists that these non-manual grammatical markings that indicate a yes/no questions are similar to the question intonation of spoken languages.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Yes/no questions differ from wh-questions as they do not differ in word order from the original statement form of the sentence, whereas wh-questions do.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] As well, in yes/no questions, the non-manual marking must be used over the whole utterance in order for it to be judged as a statement opposed to a question.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The yes/no question is the same word order as the statement form of the sentence, with the addition of non-manual grammatical markings.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings are also used for rhetorical questions, which are questions that do not intend to elicit an answer.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] To distinguish the non-manual marking for rhetorical questions from that of yes/no questions, the body is in a neutral position opposed to tilted forward, and the head is tilted in a different way than in yes/no questions.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Rhetorical questions are much more common in ASL than in English.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] [I LIKE]NEGATIVE [WHAT?]RHETORICAL, GARLIC.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This strategy is commonly used instead of signing the word 'because' for clarity or emphasis.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] PASTA I EAT ENJOY TRUE [WHY?]RHETORICAL, ITALIAN I.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL signers set up regions of space (loci) for specific referents (see above); these can then be referred to indexically by pointing at those locations with pronouns and indexical verbs.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] That is, they point to their referent, or to a locus representing their referent.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the referent is not physically present, the speaker identifies the referent and then points to a location (the *locus)* in the sign space near their body.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This locus can then be pointed at to refer to the referent.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Theoretically, any number of loci may be set up, as long as the signer and recipient remember them all, but in practice, no more than eight loci are used.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Meier 1990 demonstrates that only two grammatical persons are distinguished in ASL: First person and non-first person, as in Damin.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Both persons come in several numbers as well as with signs such as 'my' and 'by myself'.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Meier provides several arguments for believing that ASL does not formally distinguish second from third person.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, when pointing to a person that is physically present, a pronoun is equivalent to either 'you' or '(s)he' depending on the discourse.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There is nothing in the sign itself, nor in the direction of eye gaze or body posture, that can be relied on to make this distinction.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] That is, the same formal sign can refer to any of several second or third persons, which the indexic nature of the pronoun makes clear.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In English, indexic uses also occur, as in 'I need *you* to go to the store and *you* to stay here', but not so ubiquitously.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In contrast, several first-person ASL pronouns, such as the plural possessive ('our'), look different from their non-first-person equivalents, and a couple of pronouns do not occur in the first person at all, so first and non-first persons are formally distinct.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Personal pronouns have separate forms for singular ('I' and 'you/(s)he') and plural ('we' and 'you/they').
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These have possessive counterparts: 'my', 'our', 'your/his/her', 'your/their'.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In addition, there are pronoun forms which incorporate numerals from two to five ('the three of us', 'the four of you/them', etc.), though the dual pronouns are slightly idiosyncratic in form *(i.e.,* they have a K rather than 2 handshape, and the wrist nods rather than circles).
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These numeral-incorporated pronouns have no possessive equivalents.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Also among the personal pronouns are the 'self' forms ('by myself', 'by your/themselves', etc.).
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These only occur in the singular and plural (there is no numeral incorporation), and are only found as subjects.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They have derived emphatic and 'characterizing' forms, with modifications used for derivation rather like those for verbal aspect.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The 'characterizing' pronoun is used when describing someone who has just been mentioned.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It only occurs as a non-first-person singular form.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Finally, there are formal pronouns used for honored guests.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These occur as singular and plural in the non-first person, but only as singular in the first person.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL is a pro-drop language, which means that pronouns are not used when the referent is obvious from context and is not being emphasized.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Within ASL there is a class of indexical (often called 'directional') verbs.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These include the signs for 'see', 'pay', 'give', 'show', 'invite', 'help', 'send', 'bite', etc.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These verbs include an element of motion that indexes one or more referents, either physically present or set up through the referent locus system.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If there are two loci, the first indicates the subject and the second the object, direct or indirect depending on the verb, reflecting the basic word order of ASL.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, 'give' is a bi-indexical verb based on a flattened M/O handshape.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For 'I give you', the hand moves from myself toward you; for 'you give me', it moves from you to me.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The verb 'to be in pain' (index fingers pointed at each other and alternately approaching and separating) is signed at the location of the pain (head for headache, cheek for toothache, abdomen for stomachache, etc.).
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is normally done in relation to the signer's own body, regardless of the person feeling the pain, but may take also use the locus system, especially for body parts which are not normally part of the sign space, such as the leg.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are also spatial verbs such as put-up and put-below, which allow signers to specify where things are or how they moved them around.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-phabet] Like SignFont and Stokoe notation, ASL-phabet is a phonemic script, but it has been simplified to the point where there is some ambiguity, that is, one symbol can represent more than one phonemic element (handshape, location or movement).
[src:british-sign-language/asl-phabet] For example, whereas SignFont has 25 letters encoding types of movement, and Stokoe notation has 24, ASL-phabet has just 5.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-phabet] This can result in homographs (more than one sign spelled the same way).
[src:british-sign-language/asl-phabet] All together, ASL-phabet has 22 letters for handshape, 5 for location, and 5 for movement.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-phabet] They are written in that order, left-to-right, with the possibility for several letters of each type, such as two handshape letters for a two-handed sign.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-phabet] Like Stokoe notation (but unlike SignFont), the ASL-phabet does not provide symbols for facial expressions, mouthing, and other aspects of sign language structure, which may make it hard to use for extended text.
[src:british-sign-language/asl-phabet] However, it is sufficient to look up ASL words in an ASL–English dictionary.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Its core components are digits, locatives, marks and movements which are written in a fairly rigid order (though in a fairly flexible configuration) from left to right.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] The order of the writing is from left to right, top to bottom, with locatives or certain marks often beginning words.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Sentences are ended by the full stop mark ().
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Questions in written ASL are denoted by eyebrow marks bounding the question not unlike Spanish's "¿ ?." Question words or wh-questions in ASL can also form the interrogative.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] There are in total 105 characters in ASLwrite with 67 digits, five diacritic marks, twelve locatives, sixteen extramanual marks and five movement marks.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Since its creation, it has evolved to include more digits, locatives, movements and marks as well as modify those already present.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] si5s, a system built from SignWriting, was first proposed by Robert Arnold in his 2007 Gallaudet thesis *A Proposal of the Written System for ASL*.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] The ASLwrite community split from Arnold upon his decision to maintain si5s as a private venture with ASLized after the publication of his and Adrean Clark's book *How to Write American Sign Language*.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Aside from the small, but dedicated, Facebook group of around 470 in July 2023, ASLwrite is rarely used outside such online spaces.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] However, one of the most popular online ASL dictionaries, HandSpeak, has begun to incorporate ASLwrite as the primary written component of ASL definitions.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] ASLwrite is a somacheirographic system meaning that it represents the body (Greek: σῶμα *sôma* 'body') and hands (Greek: χείρ *kheír* 'hand') and relays phonemic information.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] However, it also incorporates logographs (questioning marks) and is featural.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] The general principle is to capture a single ASL word per segment, from left to right, registering non-manual feature(s), location(s), handshape(s), movement(s) and general orientation.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] It imagines the writer/speaker is looking down at their hands or viewing words from the profile such that words can be made either as if seen from straight-on or from one's profile.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] The digibet captures handshape information as well as orientation, movement and some locations.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Locatives are characters that capture location, though handshape diacritics like *edge* do capture some locations such as edge of palm.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Diacritics, such as movements, modify handshapes and can indicate small movements or small orientations.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Movements themselves are fairly flexible in their shapes and orientations, which makes digitising this script difficult.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Frontal or profile locatives – Captures the same location information, just from two perspectives.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] An example (seen on the right) is the shoulder locative is either a shoulder frontal locative that is written above or below the handshape(s).
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Handshapes – Can be written before or after the locative.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] A handshape can be oriented in 360° depending on its location and is written at the end of its movement path if there is one.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Each handshape present is written, and when more than one handshape (of one hand) is written, a movement must be present.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Movements – Larger movements or movements that affect multiple handshapes.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] When a handshape changes without overt movement, the handshapes are written left-to-right with a single movement below, similar to an underline.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Non-manual & punctuation marks – These are questioning marks such as *why*, *who*, *how* and *how*.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] The digibet is composed of handshapes called digits that are modified by diacritics and movements.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] It shares 23 handshapes with ASL's manual alphabet.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Digits are grouped together by features such as +thumb/-thumb or +closed/-closed.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] In practise, there are 67 digits in ASLwrite's digibet, though that number is growing as new digits are added representing diverse handshapes.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Moreover, other languages may adopt this system which would add increasingly more digits.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] There are five diacritics, of which one is a movement diacritic.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Movements are flexible and thus hard to capture in a digital or non-handwritten fashion.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] The movements are diverse and aim to capture the movements of the hands, arms and body.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] There are three points – an **endpoint**, a **firmpoint** and a **contactpoint** –, an **orbit mark**, a **steering** and a **crank mark** as well as the movement mark or line.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] The movement line follows the path of the hand(s) and can be as clean (e.g., – or | ) or as erratic as possible.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] The points denote the end of a handshape's path and the degree to which the motion is made.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] A contactpoint denotes an imaginary or in-the-air point with the contactpoint ending at a location and noted as being a firm ending with the firmpoint.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] The orbit mark indicates a central "point" around which the handshapes orbit; for orbital paths cut short, one would use a steering mark, and for parallel cranking motions, the crank mark would be used.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] The locatives are characters that denote a specific location on or near the signer's body.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] They are presented from a face-on and side-view.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] The two sub-classifications are **frontal** and **profile locatives**.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Non-manual marks vary quite significantly and can only be placed at the beginning or end of words or phrases.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] **Eyebrow marks** are denoted before and after the word(s) in question thus bounding the words that are modified by eyebrow marks.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] They are called: **Raised (), Knit, Wan, Slanted** and **Squint**.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Questioning marks exist in ASL as logographs that denote ASL's wh-questions such as WHO or FOR-FOR.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] They are placed after a closed word's or phrase's second eyebrow mark and can exist as an entire sentence alone.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Mouth marks are characters that relay what action the mouth is doing.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] It is placed inside the first eyebrow mark.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Body movements are non-manual, non-facial features such as **shoulder shift ()** or **head nod**.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] They, as well as **nose crinkle ()**, stand alone and can be inserted anywhere, inside and outside of eyebrow-marked phrases.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] means *Yes?* in ASL composed of , , and where the raised eyebrow marks at the beginning and the end indicate it is a yes/no question, and the hinge mark () denotes that the S handshape digit () makes a nodding motion.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] The circular point at the end is a full stop mark indicating the end of the sentence.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Unlike in English writing, the full stop mark () is employed for all sentences, even questions (as seen here).
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Breaks in the sentence, as seen below, are denoted by the shoulder shift mark ().
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] The text on the right is from Chapters 1:2–4 of the Book of Ruth.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] The first quoted text is the verse in English and the second is an ASL gloss.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] Due to the complexity of the writing system and its need for flexibility for movements, it means that producing anything in a digital format is difficult.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] However, there are efforts to create fonts headed by members of its Facebook group, notably looking at proper font creation and using current keyboard characters such as ' } ' or ' _.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] ' to achieve minor forms of communication in ASL over text.
[src:british-sign-language/aslwrite] An example phrase is " }_.U- " which means 'thank you' in ASL.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] In 2016 the British Deaf Association (BDA) said that, based on official statistics, it believes there are 151,000 people who use BSL in the UK, and 87,000 of these are deaf.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] This figure does not include professional BSL users, interpreters, translators, etc. unless they use BSL at home.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] By contrast, in the 2011 England and Wales Census 15,000 people living in England and Wales reported themselves using BSL as their main language.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] In Northern Ireland, there are about 4,500 users of BSL and 1,500 users of Irish Sign Language, an unrelated sign language.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] A hybrid version, dubbed "Northern Ireland Sign Language", is also used.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] On 18 March 2003 the UK government formally recognised BSL as a language in its own right.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] In 2022, the British Sign Language Act was passed, which legally recognised BSL as a language of England, Wales and Scotland.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] BSL is used in some educational establishments, but is not always the policy for deaf children in some local authority areas.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] As of January 2026, there is no GCSE qualification in British Sign Language available to students, but one is under development in England and planned for Wales.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The Department for Education began to develop the GCSE in 2019, but the process was delayed due to the Covid-19 pandemic.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] In June 2023, the UK Government launched a consultation for the GCSE, with teaching initially planned to begin in schools from September 2025.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] In 2024, Qualifications Wales suspended development of its GCSE in BSL, setting a new goal to introduce it to schools in Wales in 2027.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] In 2025, Ofqual ran a second consultation to gather feedback on its proposed rules for the qualification in England, releasing the results and its final decisions on the rules in November.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] GCSE exam boards who want to run the qualification in England must next make detailed offers to Ofqual for accreditation based on these regulations.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Many British television channels broadcast programmes with in-vision signing, using BSL, as well as specially made programmes aimed mainly at deaf people such as the BBC's *See Hear* and Channel 4's *VEE-TV*.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] There is also a specially dedicated British Sign Language channel, LumoTV (previously BSL Zone), established in 2008.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] All BBC channels (excluding BBC One and BBC Alba) provide in-vision signing for some of their programmes.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] BBC Two also broadcasts in-vision signed repeats of the main channel's primetime programmes between 00:00 and 05:00 each weekday and early Saturday mornings.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] It also provides signing on weekday mornings between 08:00 and 09:00.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] In 2024, over 10% of Channel 4's programming was signed, including popular shows such as Hollyoaks and Gogglebox.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Published in 1992, the British Sign Language Dictionary was compiled for the British Deaf Association by the Deaf Studies Research Unit at the University of Durham.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The dictionary was edited by David Brien, assisted by a team composed by Mary Brennan, Clark Denmark, Frances Elton, Liz Scott Gibson, Graham Turner and Dorothy Miles, among others.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] It depicts over 1,800 signs through pictures and diagrams, each sign accompanied by definitions, explanations and usage.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The signs are ordered not alphabetically, as a dictionary of the English language, but rather according to the phonological characteristics of the language.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] For example, signs that are based on the "fist" handshape come before signs based on the "open hand" handshape.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The foreword was written by Diana, Princess of Wales, who was the patron of the BDA.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The British Sign Language Corpus Project, based at the Deafness Cognition and Language Research Centre (University College London), was funded between 2008 and 2011 to provide a video corpus of BSL in four regions (Bristol, Birmingham, London and Manchester).
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] It was succeeded by the BSL SignBank, which moved the BSL Corpus online between 2011 and 2015.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] It also draws on the 1992 BSL Dictionary for its vocabulary.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Certain signs used in Scotland, for example, may not be understood immediately, or not understood at all, by those in Southern England, or vice versa.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Some signs are even more local, occurring only in certain towns or cities (such as the Manchester system of number signs).
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Likewise, some may go in or out of fashion, or evolve over time, just as terms in oral languages do.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Families may have signs unique to them to accommodate for certain situations or to describe an object that may otherwise require fingerspelling.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Although the United Kingdom and the United States share English as the predominant spoken language, British Sign Language is quite distinct from American Sign Language (ASL), having only 31% signs identical, or 44% cognate.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] BSL is also distinct from Irish Sign Language (ISL), which is more closely related to French Sign Language (LSF) and ASL.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] BSL is also distinct from Signed English, a manually coded method expressed to represent the English language.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The sign languages used in Australia and New Zealand, Auslan and New Zealand Sign Language respectively, evolved largely from 19th century BSL, and all retain the same manual alphabet and grammar and possess similar lexicons.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The sign language used in Sri Lanka is also closely related to BSL despite the oral language not being English, demonstrating variation in distance between sign languages and spoken ones.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] While private correspondence from William Stokoe hinted at a formal name for the language in 1960, the first usage of the term "British Sign Language" in an academic publication was likely by Aaron Cicourel.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The earliest known document describing the use of signing in a legal context is dated to c.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] 1324 and mentions John de Orleton, a deaf man assigning his property to a family member.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Published in 1450, the *History of the Syon Monastery at Lisbon and Brentford*, contains descriptions of signs—some of which are still in use.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The earliest evidence of signing in registry records is from a marriage ceremony between a deaf man, Thomas Tilsye and Ursula Russel on 6 February 1576 at St Martin's Church, now Leicester Cathedral.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Richard Carew's *Survey of Cornwall* (1602) includes a description of Edward Bone, a deaf servant, meeting his deaf friend John Kempe.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Bone had some knowledge of Cornish and was able to lipread, but appeared to prefer signing.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] In particular, *Chirologia* focuses on the meanings of gestures, expressions and body language, and describes signs and gestures in use at the time, some of which resemble signs still in use, while *Philocopus* explores the use of lipreading by deaf people and the possibility of deaf education.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Another writer of the same time, George Dalgarno, recognised that sign language was unrelated to English.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] British Sign Language has evolved, as all languages do, from these origins by modification, invention and importation.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Thomas Braidwood, a teacher from Edinburgh, founded 'Braidwood's Academy for the Deaf and Dumb' in 1760, which is believed to be the first school for deaf children in Britain.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The school primarily taught oral communication, however there is evidence of 'deaf signing' being used as a teaching method (albeit probably following the structure of English).
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] This *combined system* came to be known as the English method—a sort of midway point between French manualist and German oralist systems, and was the first codification of what would later develop into British Sign Language.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Joseph Watson was trained as a teacher of the deaf under Thomas Braidwood.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] He eventually left in 1792 to become the headmaster of the Asylum for the Deaf and Dumb in Bermondsey where he advocated for 'natural signing'—likely referring to the way deaf children naturally sign, as opposed to following English structure.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] This 'natural signing' is thought to be the precursor to modern BSL.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] In 1815 when Thomas Gallaudet visited England, the Braidwood school refused to teach him their methods unless he paid them.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] So instead, Gallaudet found himself in Paris, having been invited there by the much more accommodating Abbé Sicard.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Gallaudet would eventually take much of the what had learnt in France, back to the United States.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] As a consequence American Sign Language (ASL) today has a 60% similarity to modern French Sign Language and is almost unintelligible to users of British Sign Language.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] By the mid 1800s, sign was the most prominent mode of communication within deaf schools in Britain, and by 1870, there were 22 (often residential) schools found in most major cities around the country.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The Second International Congress on Education of the Deaf, also known as the Milan Conference, was held in 1880, and proscribed the use of sign language in education; for the best part of a century, sign language was no longer used in the education of deaf children.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Signing was actively discouraged in schools by punishment, and deaf education emphasised teaching deaf children to learn to lip read and finger spell, due to the prevailing belief across Europe established that signing was bad.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Since there was no (or very little) exchange of sign language within educational establishments, signing was preserved through deaf clubs or within families.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Until the 1940s, sign language skills were passed between deaf people without a unified sign language system and many deaf people lived in residential institutions.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] In 1978, the government-issued Warnock Report advocated for the mainstreaming of deaf children which led to the closure of many deaf schools.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] During this time, the Total Communication method was popularised.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] From the 1970s there has been an increasing tolerance for the language, in part due to its recognition as a natural language by linguists.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] In the 1980s, BSL started to be used as language of instruction in schools again, alongside English.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] This decade saw the start of deaf programming on British television.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Deaf scholar and activist Paddy Ladd is credited with getting sign language on television and enabling deaf children to be educated in sign.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] BSL users campaigned to have BSL recognised on an official level.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1984 mandates the provision of interpreters.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] In 1999, the Federation of Deaf People (FDP) led a 4000-strong march in London to demand the recognition of BSL as a language.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] This can be considered to mark the first political march by the modern 'British Deaf Community', as an established community.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Let Sign Shine is a campaign started by Norfolk teenager Jade Chapman, whose sister is deaf, to raise awareness of BSL and to petition for BSL to be taught in schools.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The campaign's petition to Parliament attracted support from over four thousand people.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Chapman won awards for her work including the education award category at the Bernard Matthews Youth Award 2014 for her work in raising awareness of the importance of sign language.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Having been donated £1,000 from the Bernard Matthews Youth Award, Let Sign Shine used this to start a British Sign Language course at Dereham Neatherd High School.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] In 2021, MP Rosie Cooper (a CODA) introduced the British Sign Language Bill to recognise BSL, this time as an official language (not merely its existence as had been done in 2003), which was backed by the government.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] After being dormant from June 2021, the bill began moving through Parliament on 28 January 2022, but during a meeting with stakeholders on 7 February, the language of the bill was revealed to have been pared down substantially, disappointing said stakeholders.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The British Deaf Association stated that it was 'unhappy' with this removal of language from the bill.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The British Sign Language Act received royal assent on 28th April 2022.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Linguistics is the study of language, including those like BSL that are not carried by sound.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] In all sign languages the great majority of 'words' (hand gestures) cannot be understood in other sign languages.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] How one language signs a certain number would be different from how another language signs it.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The way sentences are constructed (syntax) differs from sign language to sign language, just as with different spoken languages.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] British Sign Language is described as a 'spatial language' as it "moves signs in space".
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Like many other sign languages, BSL phonology is defined by elements such as handshape, orientation, location, movement, and non-manual features.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] There are phonological components to sign language that have no meaning alone but work together to create a meaning of a signed word: hand shape, movement, location, orientation and facial expression.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The meanings of words differ if one of these components is changed.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Signs can be identical in certain components but different in others, giving each a different meaning.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Facial expression falls under the nonmanual feature component of phonology.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] In common with other languages, whether spoken or signed, BSL has its own grammar which govern how phrases are signed.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] One important component of BSL is its use of proforms.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] A proform is "...any form that stands in the place of, or does the job of, some other form." Sentences are composed of two parts, in order: the subject and the predicate.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The subject is the topic of the sentence, while the predicate is the commentary about the subject.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Question words are generally at the end of a sentence.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Topic-comment means that the topic of the signed conversation is first established, followed by an elaboration of the topic, being the 'comment' component.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The canonical word order outside of the topic–comment structure is object–subject–verb (OSV), and noun phrases are head-initial.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The language continues to evolve as older signs such as *alms* and *pawnbroker* have fallen out of use and new signs such as *internet* and *laser* have been coined.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The evolution of the language and its changing level of acceptance meant that older users tend to use more finger spelling while younger ones make use of a wider range of signs.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] In 2019, over 100 signs for scientific terms, including 'deoxyribonucleotide' and 'deoxyribonucleoside', were added to BSL, after being conceived by Liam Mcmulkin, a deaf graduate of the University of Dundee, who had found finger-spelling such words tiresome, during his degree course.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Similarly, architects Chris Laing and Adolfs Kristapsons developed a project called SignStrokes which developed new signs for the built environment, having not wanted to continuously make new signs for different architectural concepts.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] British Sign Language can be learnt from formal institutions throughout the UK and three examination systems exist.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Courses are provided by community colleges, local centres for deaf people and private organisations.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] A teaching qualification programme was started by the British Deaf Association in 1984 at the University of Durham, called BSL Tutor Training Course, which closed in 1999.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] National awarding organisations run training for BSL teachers.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Each of these organisations has its own curriculum, teaching materials and resources.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] There are two qualification routes: via post-graduate studies, or via National Vocational Qualifications.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Deaf studies undergraduate courses with specific streams for sign language interpreting exist at several British universities; post-graduate level interpreting diplomas are also on offer from universities and one private company.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Course entry requirements vary from no previous knowledge of BSL to NVQ level 6 BSL (or equivalent).
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The qualification process allows interpreters to register with the National Registers of Communication Professionals with Deaf and Deafblind People (NRCPD), a voluntary regulator.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Registrants are asked to self-certify that they have both cleared a DBS (Disclosure and Barring Service) check and are covered by professional indemnity insurance.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Completing a level 3 BSL language assessment and enrolling on an approved interpreting course allows applications to register as a TSLI (Trainee Sign Language Interpreter).
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] After completing an approved interpreting course, trainees can then apply to achieve RSLI (Registered Sign Language Interpreter) status.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] RSLIs are currently required by NRCPD to log Continuous Professional Development activities.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Post-qualification, specialist training is still considered necessary to work in specific critical domains.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] Communication support workers (CSWs) are professionals who support the communication of deaf students in education at all ages, and deaf people in many areas of work, using British Sign Language and other communication methods such as Sign Supported English.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] The qualifications and experience of CSWs vary: some are fully qualified interpreters, others are not.
[src:british-sign-language/british-sign-language] There are currently two well-established BSL language learning apps and web platforms: Bright BSL and Lingvano.
